    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>Stuff &amp; Things</h2>
          <p>Our curated list of recent, suggested listening, reading and viewing.</p>

          <dl>
            <dt>
              <svg><use xlink:href="#youtube" /></svg> 
              <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XBu92r3ezTA">How to Color Grade with Julieanne KostᅵAdobe Lightroom</a>
            </dt>
            <dd>Julieanne Kost walks through Lightroom's new(-ish?) color grading tools, which ought to seem very familiar to Capture One Pro users as well.</dd>

            <dt>
              <svg><use xlink:href="#youtube" /></svg> 
              <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QyqykIFqNoY">The Movement to Save Our Night Skies</a>
            </dt>
            <dd>From PBS Terra, exploring one town's mission to become a Dark Sky Community and reclaim the darkness of night. Follow researchers in Western Colorado to discover how the darkness of night is not just important to experience the wonders of the cosmos, it's vital to maintaining healthy ecosystems, and saving the epic migrations of America's birds.</dd>

            <dt>
              <svg><use xlink:href="#youtube" /></svg> 
              <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iSm0nvOa07w">Why Tree Planting Campaigns Don't Work</a>
            </dt>
            <dd>Another from PBS Terra. In 2019, a Turkey tree planting campaign set a world record. Three months later, 90% of those saplings were dead. Planting trees to replace old-growth forests is a common solution, but it typically does not solve the problem.</dd>

            <dt>
              <svg><use xlink:href="#youtube" /></svg>
              <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G5lKmUw_Vxs">Music Pick: "The Hills" by Rachel Chinouriri</a>
            </dt>
            <dd>A couple years ago, I latched onto Rachel Chinouriri's <cite>4º In Winter EP</cite> with a ferocity reserved for few things. I absolutely adore that record. And I've loved everything she's done since then, her latest, "The Hills", being no exception. I particularly enjoy the sour guitars, marking "The Hills" as Chinouriri's most rock-oriented track yet.</dd>
          </dl>
        </mj-text>        
